net.java.jddac.jmdi.comm.xml
Class WbxmlObjectCoder

java.lang.Object
  net.java.jddac.jmdi.comm.xml.WbxmlObjectCoder
All Implemented Interfaces:
ObjectCoder
public class WbxmlObjectCoder
extends java.lang.Object
implements ObjectCoder

Generates a WXML document. This WBXML Coder is highly customized for use with jddac and is far from being a generic encoder. Due to the need to encode arrays of numeric values as well as the limited number of fundamental types to encode for JDDAC, the approach to encode is more or less brute force. This leads to faster encoding but of course is much less extensible. See http://www.w3.org/TR/wbxml/ for official encoding specs. The following examples illustrate the types of objects that can be coded using regular XML as an example: WBXML Quick Ref [Attributes][Content] Tag bits: 7 (msb) : 1 if attributes follow 6 : 1 if tag has content. 0-5 : Tag identity (literal allowed) Attribute coding 7 (msb) : 0 if this is the start of an attribute (must include the whole name but can include zero or more of the value). : 1 means this is a well known string 0-6 : identity, LITERAL only allowed for attribute name portion thru '=' Thus, the end of a single attribute is detected by msb=0 (a second attribute follows) or the special end attributes token (WBXML_END). Content coding Content coding utilizes globally defined tokens which allow encoding of strings, opaque data, and document type specific 'extensions'. Content coding is terminated by the end token (WBXML_END). Numeric arrays are encoded as an opaque stream of bytes with each array element of fixed length (e.g. ints use 4 bytes per array element). If the Tag bit 6 is zero then no contents or content END tag are encoded. The following 'extensions' are utilized: WBXML_EXT_T_0 - a 32 bit integer value WBXML_EXT_T_1 - most significant 32 bits of a 64 bit integer value WBXML_EXT_T_2 - least significant 32 bits of 64 bit integer value The Code space and attribute space are currently shared implicitly which limits the attribute space to 59 values as that is the limit on code space tags.
